## Algebras

In this section we define the notion of an algebraic structure whose *domain* (or "carrier" or "universe") is a setoid. Our first goal is to develop a working vocabulary and formal types for classical (single-sorted, set-based) universal algebra.

### <a id="signatures-of-an-algebra">Signatures of an algebra</a>

In [model theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model_theory), the *signature* `ùëÜ = (ùê∂, ùêπ, ùëÖ, œÅ)` of a structure consists of three (possibly empty) sets `ùê∂`, `ùêπ`, and `ùëÖ`---called *constant symbols*, *function symbols*, and *relation symbols*, respectively---along with a function `œÅ : ùê∂ + ùêπ + ùëÖ ‚Üí ùëÅ` that assigns an *arity* to each symbol. Often, but not always, `ùëÅ` is taken to be the set of natural numbers.

As our focus here is universal algebra, we are more concerned with the restricted notion of an *algebraic signature* (or *signature* for algebraic structures), by which we mean a pair `ùëÜ = (F, œÅ)` consisting of a collection `ùêπ` of *operation symbols* and an *arity function* `œÅ : F ‚Üí N` that maps each operation symbol to its arity; here, ùëÅ denotes the *arity type*. Heuristically, the arity `œÅ f` of an operation symbol `f ‚àà F` may be thought of as the "number of arguments" that `f` takes as "input".

If the arity of `f` is `n`, then we call `f` an `n`-*ary* operation symbol.  In case `n` is 0 (or 1 or 2 or 3, respectively) we call the function *nullary* (or *unary* or *binary* or *ternary*, respectively).

If `A` is a set and `f` is a (`œÅ f`)-ary operation on `A`, then the arguments of `f` form a (`œÅ f`)-tuple, say, `(a 0, a 1, ‚Ä¶, a (œÅf-1))`, which may be viewed as the graph of a function, say, `a : œÅf ‚Üí A`. When the codomain of `œÅ` is `‚Ñï`, we may view `œÅ f` as the finite set `{0, 1, ‚Ä¶, œÅf - 1}`. Thus, by identifying the `œÅf`-th power of `A` with the type `œÅ f ‚Üí A` of functions from `{0, 1, ‚Ä¶, œÅf - 1}` to `A`, we identify the collection of all tuples of arguments of `f` with the function type `(œÅf ‚Üí A) ‚Üí A`.

#### <a id="signature-type">Signature type</a>

The [agda-algebras][] library represents a *signature* as an inhabitant of the following dependent pair type.

```
Signature : (ùìû ùì• : Level) ‚Üí Type (lsuc (ùìû ‚äî ùì•))
Signature ùìû ùì• = Œ£[ F ‚àà Type ùìû ] (F ‚Üí Type ùì•)
```

Using special syntax for the first and second projections---`‚à£_‚à£` and `‚à•_‚à•`, respectively---if `ùëÜ : Signature ùìû ùì•` is a signature, then

* `‚à£ ùëÜ ‚à£` denotes the set of operation symbols;
* `‚à• ùëÜ ‚à•` denotes the arity function.

Thus, if `ùëì : ‚à£ ùëÜ ‚à£` is an operation symbol in the signature `ùëÜ`, then `‚à• ùëÜ ‚à• ùëì` is the arity of `ùëì`.

We need to augment the ordinary `Signature` type so that it supports algebras over setoid domains.
To do so, we define an operator `‚ü®_‚ü©` which translates an ordinary signature into a setoid signature, that is, a signature over a setoid domain.  But first we must resolve a techinical issue involving dependent types that we now describe.

Suppose we are given two operations `f` and `g` and we have a tuple of arguments for `f`, say, `u : ‚à• ùëÜ ‚à• f ‚Üí A`, and a tuple of arguments for `g`, say, `v : ‚à• ùëÜ ‚à• g ‚Üí A`.  If we know that `f` is identically equal to `g`---that is, `f ‚â° g` (intensionally)---then we should be able to check whether `u` and `v` are pointwise equal.  The problem here is that `u` and `v` ostensibly inhabit different types.  To compare `u` and `v` we must convince Agda that, from `f ‚â° g` we can deduce that `u` and `v` are actually of the same type. The type `EqArgs` (defined below, and adapted from Andreas Abel's development [ref needed]) resolves this technical issue nicely.

\begin{code}

EqArgs :  {ùëÜ : Signature ùìû ùì•}{Œæ : Setoid Œ± œÅ·µÉ}
 ‚Üí        ‚àÄ {f g} ‚Üí f ‚â° g ‚Üí (‚à• ùëÜ ‚à• f ‚Üí Carrier Œæ) ‚Üí (‚à• ùëÜ ‚à• g ‚Üí Carrier Œæ) ‚Üí Type (ùì• ‚äî œÅ·µÉ)

EqArgs {Œæ = Œæ} ‚â°.refl u v = ‚àÄ i ‚Üí u i ‚âà v i where open Setoid Œæ using ( _‚âà_ )

\end{code}

Now we are ready to define the `‚ü®_‚ü©` operator, which translates an ordinary signature into a setoid signature.

\begin{code}

module _ where
 open Setoid        using ( _‚âà_ )
 open IsEquivalence using ( refl ; sym ; trans )

 ‚ü®_‚ü© : Signature ùìû ùì• ‚Üí Setoid Œ± œÅ·µÉ ‚Üí Setoid _ _

